<p><b><a name="symptoms" class="bookmark"></a></b></p>.<p></p>.<p>As the disease progresses, symptoms may become more severe or even permanent. Many people with arachnoiditis are unable to work and suffer significant disability because they are in constant pain.</p>.<p><b><a name="causes_of_arachnoiditis" class="bookmark"></a></b></p>.<p></p>.<p><b><a name="making_the_diagnosis" class="bookmark"></a></b></p>.<p></p>.<p><i>Note: Myelograms with the radiographic contrast currently in use, combined with CAT scanning, are not considered to be responsible for causing arachnoiditis or causing it to worsen.</i></p>.<p><b><a name="treating_arachnoiditis" class="bookmark"></a></b></p>.<p></p>.<p><font face="Arial" size="1">Reviewed by the doctors at The Cleveland Clinic Neuroscience Center.<br>Edited by Charlotte E. Grayson, MD, WebMD, September 2004.<br><br>Portions of this page Â© The Cleveland Clinic 2000-2005</font><span id="cntid"></span></p>